text=>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary:Trimming excess white space from command returns is important!%0aParent:(Technology.)Development%0aIncludeMe:[[(Technology.)Development]]%0aCategories:[[!Articles]]%0aTags: best practices%0a(:tags-hide best practices :)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a[[#excerpt]]%0aWhen calling commands from within another language via a shell exec, often times the command returns with trailing white space that you don't want. %0a[[#excerptend]]%0a%0a%0a!!PHP%0a%0aIn PHP, you can execute a shell command via either the [[http://us.php.net/manual/en/language.operators.execution.php|backtick operators]] or @@[[http://us.php.net/manual/en/function.shell-exec.php|shell_exec()]]@@%0a%0aThe way to eliminate this is with the @@[[http://us.php.net/manual/en/function.trim.php|trim()]]@@ or @@[[http://us.php.net/manual/en/function.rtrim.php|rtrim()]]@@ functions:%0a%0a(:source lang=php linenum header="In PHP":)%0a$result = rtrim(`date "+%25Y-%25m-%25d"`);%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0a!!Perl%0a%0aIn perl, the backtick operator will run a shell command. Here, @@chomp()@@ does the work to get rid of trailing white space.%0a%0a(:source lang=perl linenum header="In Perl":)%0amy $result = `date "+%25Y-%25m-%25d"`;%0achomp($result);%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0a!!Ruby%0aAs in perl, the backtick operator does the work, and chomp gets rid of the end.%0a(:source lang=ruby linenum header="In Ruby":)%0aresult = `date "+%25Y-%25m-%25d"`.chomp%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0a
